<HEAD>Eastern Caribbean Prepares for Hurricane Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `At 9 p.m. ..., to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT
position, track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After being brushed by several hurricanes this year,
the eastern <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> islands may get the brunt of Hurricane Hugo as
it churns westward with 150 mph winds, forecasters said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   ``It looks like this one is not going to miss the islands like
the others,'' said <PERSON>Jack Beven</PERSON>, a forecaster at the <ORGANIZATION>National
Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>. ``It's on the most
southerly course of any this year and that should keep it down in
the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> longer.''
   A hurricane warning was posted <DATE>Friday</DATE> from <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION> to the
<ORGANIZATION>British Virgin Islands</ORGANIZATION>, and a hurricane watch was issued for the
<ORGANIZATION>U.S. Virgin Islands</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>. A tropical storm watch was
issued for the islands of <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>St. Vincent</LOCATION>.
   Rough seas have been reported around the islands since <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   Forecasters described the force four hurricane as ``extremely
dangerous.'' Category five is the scale's highest rank.
   At <TIME>10:30 p.m. EDT</TIME>, Hugo's center was near 14.9 north latitude and
56.6 west longitude, or about 340 miles east southeast of the French
resort island of <LOCATION>Guadeloupe</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>Leeward Islands</LOCATION>. The storm was
moving west at 15 mph.
   With nothing in the atmosphere to divert it or sap its power,
Hugo was expected to remain on its westerly course and strengthen
somewhat during the next 24 hours, according to reports from an <ORGANIZATION>Air
Force</ORGANIZATION> reconnaissance plane.
   <PERSON>Beven</PERSON> said the center of the system could reach the <LOCATION>Leeward
Islands</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> and may move toward <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION> over the
weekend. Rainfall amounts of five to 10 inches is expected in the
path of the hurricane.
   Three other hurricanes this year _ Dean, <PERSON>Erin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> _
turned north toward <LOCATION>Bermuda</LOCATION> before reaching the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>.
   But Hugo's southern course is reminiscent of Hurricane Gilbert,
which pounded <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION> and the Mexican mainland <DATE>last September</DATE>. Hugo
was upgraded <DATE>Friday</DATE> to a force 4 storm. Gilbert was a 5, the scale's
highest rank.
   Hugo is the eighth named storm of the present <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> hurricane
season, which runs from <DATE>June 1</DATE> to <DATE>Nov. 30</DATE>. Tropical storms have
maximum sustained winds of 39 mph, and reach hurricane status when
winds reach 74 mph.
</TEXT>
