<HEAD>Forecasters Say Hurricane Could Make Landfall By Week's End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th, ``We were ..., to UPDATE with report
from Air Force reconnaissance mission.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forecasters consulted computers, satellites and
yellowing hurricane charts <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in a frantic effort to plot the
course of Hurricane Hugo, which might hit the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> this
<DATE>weekend</DATE>.
   Then again, it might not.
   ``When you look out two to three days in the future, that's when
we have our most difficult problems,'' said <PERSON>Bob Sheets</PERSON>, director of
the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>. ``We have a
lot of different things going on.''
   Forecasters said <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> residents from the <LOCATION>Florida Keys</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>North
Carolina</LOCATION> should watch Hugo's uncertain path carefully. The
hurricane, leaving devastation behind in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>, was moving
past the <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION> and could affect <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> by <DATE>Friday</DATE>, forecasters
said.
   They added, however, that it could also miss the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>
entirely.
   A variety of weather factors, some as far away as <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> and the
<LOCATION>Rocky Mountains</LOCATION>, could determine Hugo's course. But the most likely
effect will come from the combination of a low-pressure system
moving west across southern <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION> and a broad high-pressure ridge,
the ``Bermuda High,'' to Hugo's north.
   The high-pressure system probably will block Hugo from spinning
harmlessly out into the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>, as Hurricane <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> did last
week, forecasters said, while the low-pressure system could lure
Hugo westward.
   Forecasters said the varying factors also would affect the
storm's strength, which was slowly rebuilding <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> after falling
from 140 mph winds to 105 mph.
   Forecasters watched data spit out of advanced computers, studied
satellite maps and reconnaissance photos flown back on <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>
``hurricane hunter'' planes, and even pulled out old hurricane
charts to see what storms similar to Hugo have done.
   ``We were just looking through a bunch of the old charts,''
Sheets said. ``They've done everything. They've done loopity-loops,
they've gone into south <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>, they've gone into central <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>,
all the way up to the <LOCATION>Carolinas</LOCATION>.''
   An <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> reconnaissance crew that flew into Hugo <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> said
the eye was about 30 to 40 miles across and the pressure had risen
to about 965 millibars _ a sign of weakening.
   ``It's weaker than in the past few days, but it's still a
significant hurricane,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON>Dave Carlisle</PERSON>.
   Hurricane <PERSON>David</PERSON>, a destructive hurricane that hit eastern
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> islands 10 years ago, swept past <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>, hit the
island of <LOCATION>Hispaniola</LOCATION>, moved through the western <LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION>, then made
landfall on <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>'s middle east coast.
   So far, <PERSON>Hugo</PERSON> has moved from the eastern <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> across <LOCATION>Puerto
Rico</LOCATION>, then away from <LOCATION>Hispaniola</LOCATION> and was headed slightly east of the
<LOCATION>Bahamas</LOCATION>.
   Computer models that use all available weather data, past records
and physics equations were laying out conflicting futures for Hugo,
Sheets said.
   The best advice forecasters could offer, Sheets said, was for
coastal residents across the southeastern <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to be ready.
</TEXT>
