<HEAD>Hurricane Hugo Slows Tropical Storm Iris' Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to UPDATE with 6 a.m. position; picks up 5th graf
pvs, `The storm...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Iris and its 60 mph winds swirled in
the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> as Hurricane Hugo devasted the eastern <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>.
   Iris' further strengthening was unlikely through <TIME>this evening</TIME>,
according to hurricane specialist <PERSON>Gil Clark</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>National
Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>.
   Even so, the governments of <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>St. Vincent</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION>
issued warnings for <ORGANIZATION>Iris</ORGANIZATION>, the ninth named storm of the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>
hurricane season, which ends in <DATE>November</DATE>. Forecasters warned
residents of the <LOCATION>Leeward Islands</LOCATION>, raked by <PERSON>Hugo</PERSON>, to keep an eye on
Iris.
   At <TIME>6 a.m. EDT</TIME> <DATE>today</DATE>, <PERSON>Iris</PERSON>' center was near 18.7 north latitude
and 57.9 west longitude, or about 265 miles east of the <LOCATION>Leeward
Islands</LOCATION>. It was moving north-northwest at about 17 mph.
   The storm was expected to hold that course at a slightly slower
pace today.
   Tropical depressions become named storms when their top sustained
winds reach 39 mph. Iris became a storm <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
</TEXT>
