<HEAD>Northeastern Caribbean Awaits `Extremely Dangerous' Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3-4th grafs, `At 9 a.m....', to UPDATE location, motion
speed. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The storm's...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo, the most powerful storm to hit the
northeastern <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> in a decade, was bearing down on the <LOCATION>Leeward
Islands</LOCATION> <DATE>today</DATE> with 140 mph winds and a 10-foot wall of water.
   ``This is an extremely dangerous hurricane,'' hurricane
specialist <PERSON>Max Mayfield</PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban
<LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION> said. ``This is stonger than Hurricane <PERSON>David</PERSON> back in
<DATE>1979</DATE>,'' which left 1,200 dead in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>.
   At <TIME>noon EDT</TIME> <DATE>today</DATE>, Hugo's center near 15.6 north latitude and
59.0 west longitude, or about 175 miles east-southeast of the French
resort island of <LOCATION>Guadeloupe</LOCATION> in the <LOCATION>Leeward Islands</LOCATION>. It was expected
to hit the island this afternoon or tonight, said forecaster <PERSON>Martin
Nelson</PERSON>, before moving in the direction of <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>.
   The hurricane was moving west at 14 mph, sending showers and
gusty winds to the eastern edge of the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>.
   The storm's strength flucutated <TIME>this morning</TIME>, dipping from 150
mph at <TIME>6 a.m.</TIME> to 140 mph at <TIME>9 a.m</TIME>. It was expected to continue to do
so as the size of the eye contracts and expands, forecasters said,
but storm-force winds of 39 mph and above extend 150 miles from the
center.
   In <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Air France</ORGANIZATION> announced it was canceling all three of its
flights scheduled today to <LOCATION>Martinique</LOCATION> because of the storm.
Miami-based <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION> planned no cancellations or reroutings
today, but spokesman <PERSON>Robin Matell</PERSON> said, ``We'll keep monitoring it
very closely.''
   Forecasters won't be able to tell for five or six days whether
Hugo will hit the coastal <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, forecaster <PERSON>Jim Gross</PERSON> said.
   A hurricane warning was posted from <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION> north to <LOCATION>St. Martin</LOCATION>
including the <ORGANIZATION>British Virgin Islands</ORGANIZATION>, and a hurricane watch the <LOCATION>U.S.
Virgin Islands</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION> may be upgraded to a warning today. A
tropical storm watch was in effect for the islands of <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>St. Vincent</LOCATION>, according to the hurricane center.
   Forecasters classed the hurricane in Category 4, meaning it is
considered capable of extreme damage. If its sustained winds grow to
155 mph, it would be classified in Category 5, capable of
catastrophic damage. Only two Category 5 hurricanes have hit the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> since record-keeping began; the latest, <PERSON>Camille</PERSON> in
<DATE>1969</DATE>, killed 256 people.
   Islanders were warned to expect rainfall amounts of 5 to 10
inches and a storm surge with waves 10 feet higher than normal.
   <LOCATION>Dominica</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Guadeloupe</LOCATION>'s closest neighbor to the south, has only
recently recovered from the destruction <PERSON>David</PERSON> wrought 10 years ago,
when floods and mud slides poured down from mountains onto coastal
towns and villages.
   On <LOCATION>Martinique</LOCATION>, the next island in the chain, school officials
canceled classes today.
   A disaster response team from <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Metro Dade Fire Department</ORGANIZATION>
established a communications center in <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION>, about 200 miles
south of Hugo's path, to assess damage and coordinate emergency
medical treatment throughout the <LOCATION>Leeward Islands</LOCATION>.
   At the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> station in <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>,
guardsmen were preparing for the storm <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   ``You go around and police the area and pick up anything that can
become a missile hazard,'' Petty Officer <PERSON>Alan Burd</PERSON> said.
   The island chain has escaped the worst of previous hurricanes
this year. Dean, <PERSON>Erin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> turned north toward <LOCATION>Bermuda</LOCATION>
before reaching the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>. This time, there were no signs of the
lowering atmospheric pressure that veered the others away.
   Hugo is the eighth named storm of the current <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> hurricane
season, which runs from <DATE>June 1</DATE> to <DATE>Nov. 30</DATE>. Tropical storms have
maximum sustained winds of 39 mph and reach hurricane status when
winds reach 74 mph.
</TEXT>
