<HEAD>Costly 1989 Atlantic Season Ends With Tropical Storm Karen Forming
Near Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with depression forming into Tropical
Storm Karen, UPDATES total of named storms. PICKS UP 14th graf, `Last year
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <DATE>1989</DATE> hurricane season, marked by the costliest
storm in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> history, officially ended today with yet another
tropical storm forming in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>.
   At <TIME>8 a.m. EST</TIME>, <ORGANIZATION>Tropical Storm Karen</ORGANIZATION>, with 50 mph winds, was
about 125 miles south-southwest of <LOCATION>Havana</LOCATION> and was not expected to
strengthen, said the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral
Gables</LOCATION>. It was drifttng toward <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION> at about 5 mph.
   Depressions become named storms when their sustained winds reach
39 mph; hurricanes have winds of at least 74 mph. <PERSON>Karen</PERSON> is the 11th
named storm of the season, which began <DATE>June 1</DATE>.
   The six-month season was far less deadly than <DATE>1988</DATE>'s, in which
550 people died in storms.
   This year's storms killed 84 people, including 56 in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>, said meteorologist <PERSON>Mark Zimmer</PERSON>. Hurricane Hugo was blamed
for 49 deaths, including 21 in this country. It slammed into <LOCATION>South
Carolina</LOCATION> on <DATE>Sept. 21</DATE>.
   ``I've seen greater damage in smaller areas,'' said <PERSON>Bob Sheets</PERSON>,
director of the hurricane center. ``But I've never seen it on such
a large scale where you go mile after mile with such massive
damage.''
   Overall damage from Hugo totaled about <MONEY>$10 billion</MONEY>. In the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, it caused a record storm damage of about <MONEY>$7 billion</MONEY>.
Most of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> damage was around <LOCATION>Charleston</LOCATION>.
   The <LOCATION>U.S. Virgin Islands</LOCATION> are racing to recover from Hugo in time
for the tourist season.
   ``We are still in a sense reeling from the effects of Hugo but
that didn't dampen our spirit,'' said <PERSON>Alexander A. Ferrelly</PERSON>,
governor of the <LOCATION>U.S. Virgin Islands</LOCATION>. He said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that <LOCATION>St.
Thomas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>St. John</LOCATION> are ready for winter tourists and <ORGANIZATION>St. Croix</ORGANIZATION>
would be ready by early <DATE>1990</DATE>.
   It was the most expensive disaster for the <ORGANIZATION>American Red Cross</ORGANIZATION>
since the organization began 110 years ago. Latest figures show the
agency has spent about <MONEY>$38 million</MONEY> in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and the
<LOCATION>Carolinas</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Michael Caudill</PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   The hurricane season, which began <DATE>June 1</DATE>, had four tropical
storms, counting <PERSON>Karen</PERSON>, and seven hurricanes. The storms also were
stronger than usual, said Sheets.
   Last year, there were seven tropical storms and five hurricanes.
The <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> season usually has 10 named storms. Normally, only
five or six whip up the 74-mph sustained winds to become a
hurricane.
   Hugo, the fifth major <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> hurricane in the last decade to
reach <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> shores, may have marked the end of a 30-year period of
fewer, weaker hurricanes, Sheets said.
   ``There have been fewer of the stronger hurricanes making
landfall since the <DATE>1960s</DATE>,'' Sheets said. ``Now maybe we're starting
to return to more normal activity like we had in the <DATE>'50s</DATE> and
<DATE>'60s</DATE>.''
   During the <DATE>1950s</DATE>, eight major hurricanes hit the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>,
while seven struck the following decade.
   After Hugo, the most damaging tropical system this year was
<ORGANIZATION>Tropical Storm Allison</ORGANIZATION>. It dumped large amounts of rain and caused
11 deaths and <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> damage in <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
