<HEAD>Hugo Strengthens While Gabrielle Fades</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with 10:30 p.m. EDT positions, courses, wind
speeds.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Hugo would soon strengthen into a
hurricane as it churned across the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> toward the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>,
forecasters said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, and <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> whipped up heavy swells as
it moved away from <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION>.
   Hugo, the eighth named storm of this <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> hurricane season,
had winds of 65 mph with stronger gusts in squalls, and forecasters
said conditions were right for it to grow stronger.
   ``It still looks impressive on the satellite imagery, meaning it
has continued to strengthen some,'' forecaster <PERSON>Max Mayfield</PERSON> of the
<ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION> said, adding that
Hugo could be up to 74 mph hurricane-strength winds in a day or two.
   At <TIME>10:30 p.m. EDT</TIME>, Hugo's center was near latitude 12.9 north and
longitude 39.0 west, or about 930 miles west-southwest of the
westernmost <LOCATION>Cape Verde</LOCATION> islands. It was headed west at about 20 mph
and was on a path that could take it to the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> in about five
days, forecasters said.
   Tropical Storm <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON>'s winds were down to 40 mph, but still
causing swells as high as 16 feet along the south coast of <LOCATION>Nova
Scotia</LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION>New England</LOCATION>, forecasters said.
   Gabrielle was expected to weaken as it accelerated to the
northeast over northern <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> waters.
   At <TIME>10:30 p.m. EDT</TIME>, <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON>'s center was near latitude 41.7
north, longitude 55.0 west, or about 345 miles south southwest of
<LOCATION>Cape Race</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Newfoundland</LOCATION>. It was drifting east-northeast at about 10
mph.
</TEXT>
