<HEAD>Hurricane Hugo Hits Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo brushed across <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, bringing
sustained winds near 125 mph and heavy rain, causing extensive
damage and interfering with communications.
   Hugo, the most powerful storm to strike the region in a decade,
was blamed for at least 14 deaths.
   Meteorologist <PERSON>Jesse Moore</PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> said
it was too early to tell if Hugo would strike the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> mainland. He
said it was expected to be off the southeastern Bahamas by <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>
and ``after that, it's anybody's guess.''
   Behind Hugo, Tropical Storm Iris was about 300 miles from the
Lesser Antilles with a maximum sustained wind speed of around 50
mph. Strengthening was not expected because of the proximity of Hugo.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were widespread across much
of the <LOCATION>Florida Peninsula</LOCATION>, south of a frontal system in very warm
humid air. Hail the size of golf balls pelted <LOCATION>Amelia Island</LOCATION> during
the morning, the <ORGANIZATION>National Weather Service</ORGANIZATION> said. A tornado was
reported at <LOCATION>Fernandina Beach</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Amelia Island</LOCATION>, the weather service
said.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the central <LOCATION>Pacific
Coast</LOCATION> and into the northern Rockies as low pressure in the upper
atmosphere developed over <LOCATION>Northern California</LOCATION>. Street flooding was
reported in parts of <LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, the weather service said.
   Temperatures around the nation at <TIME>3 p.m. EDT</TIME> ranged from 38
degrees at <LOCATION>Truckee</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, to 94 at <LOCATION>Brownsville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>. <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s
low in the Lower 48 states was 30 at both <PERSON>Burns</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Redmond</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ore</LOCATION>.
   For <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, widespread showers and isolated thunderstorms were
forecast from central and <LOCATION>Southern California</LOCATION> into <LOCATION>Wyoming</LOCATION> and
central <LOCATION>South Dakota</LOCATION>. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were
forecast from <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> across the southern and middle <LOCATION>Atlantic Coast</LOCATION>.
   Highs only in the 60s were predicted across the <LOCATION>Pacific
Northwest</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Great Basin of Nevada</LOCATION> and western <LOCATION>Utah</LOCATION>, and the
northern parts of <LOCATION>New England</LOCATION>; in the low to mid 90s across much of
<LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>; and in the 70s or 80s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
