<HEAD>Oil Rig Workers Flee as Storm Jerry Threatens Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with noon EDT advisory, clarify
that landfall not expected until Sunday at the earliest. Picks up 8th graf
pvs, `Tides through...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of workers fled oil rigs in the <LOCATION>Gulf
of Mexico</LOCATION> as Tropical Storm <PERSON>Jerry</PERSON> inched toward the coasts of <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION>.
   A hurricane watch was issued <TIME>this morning</TIME> for the coast from
<LOCATION>Port Arthur</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, to the mouth of the <LOCATION>Mississippi River</LOCATION>, with
landfall somewhere along that area forecast for <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at the
earliest.
   The storm weakened slightly <TIME>this morning</TIME> and also was found to
be farther away from land than first thought and moving more
slowly, said forecasters at the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Coral
Gables</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla</LOCATION>.
   Jerry developed rapidly from a tropical depression off the
Mexican coast and by early today had maximum sustained winds of 70
mph. By <TIME>late morning</TIME>, though, the winds had eased to 65 mph.
   Forecasters said conditions were not favorable for a major
increase in storm strength, but noted that even a relatively slight
increase could bring the storm up to hurricane strength, defined as
74 mph or more.
   Evacuations from the oil rigs began early <DATE>Friday</DATE>, soon after
<PERSON>Jerry</PERSON> reached tropical storm strength in the southwestern gulf,
stirring up rough seas. Officials said more than 4,000 workers
would be brought to shore if the rigs were all shut down.
   ``We started as soon as it became a tropical storm,'' <ORGANIZATION>Shell Oil</ORGANIZATION>
spokeswoman <PERSON>Wendy Jacobs</PERSON> said. ``Everyone knows you don't take any
chances with these.''
   At noon EDT <DATE>today</DATE>, <PERSON>Jerry</PERSON>'s center was near 24.9 north latitude
and 93.1 west longitude, about 400 miles south southwest of <LOCATION>New
Orleans</LOCATION>. The storm was moving north at 6 mph, more slowly than
forecasters thought earlier in the day.
   The system's rough seas could coincide with unusually high tides
expected all week because of an unusual alignment of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, Sun
and <PERSON>Moon</PERSON>.
   Tides through <DATE>Friday</DATE> were expected to peak at their highest
levels in a decade, <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> said, perhaps a foot above their usual
highs in the gulf.
   Jerry is the strongest tropical weather system since Hurricane
Hugo ravaged the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and coastal <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION> <DATE>last month</DATE>.
The storm, which killed 33 in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and 29 on the mainland
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, hit <LOCATION>Charleston</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>S.C.</LOCATION>, late <DATE>Sept. 21</DATE>.
   Storm preparations were under way along the gulf coast.
   On <LOCATION>Grand Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>La.</LOCATION>, in the gulf south of <LOCATION>New Orleans</LOCATION>,
officials readied evacuation plans for 2,000 residents.
   ``We just have to play it hour-by-hour and see what happens, but
when there's a storm in the Gulf it kind of raises everybody's
hackles a bit,'' said <PERSON>Pete Picou</PERSON>, civil defense director of <PERSON>Cameron
Parish</PERSON> on the southwestern <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> coast. ``Down here you can't
ever take them for granted.''
</TEXT>
