<HEAD>Gabrielle Still Weakening; New Depression Being Watched</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout TO UPDATE with storms' 10:30 p.m. EDT position,
speed and motion; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gabrielle, dwindled from a hurricane to a tropical
storm, lost more its punch <DATE>Monday</DATE> while forecasters began watching a
new tropical depression shaping up in the area where <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> got
its start.
   Gabrielle, lingering south of <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION>, lost its hurricane
status late <DATE>Sunday</DATE> when its maximum sustained wind speed dropped
below the 74 mph minimum. By <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>, it had slowed to 45 mph.
   The depression, the 11th since the <DATE>1989</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Atlantic Hurricane</ORGANIZATION> season
began <DATE>June 1</DATE>, formed from a tropical wave off <LOCATION>West Africa</LOCATION>. It had a
maximum sustained wind speed of 45 mph and was expected to reach
tropical-storm strength of 39 mph by noon <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. It would be named
Hugo.
   ``This is the peak of the tropical storm season and these
tropical waves are moving off the coast of <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> every three or
four days like clockwork,'' said forecaster <PERSON>Max Mayfield</PERSON> of the
<ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>.
   Neither it nor <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> posed any immediate threat to land,
although <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON>'s wind still created unusually high surf
conditions along the southern coast of <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>U.S. East
Coast</LOCATION> north of <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>.
   During the <DATE>weekend</DATE>, swells, undertow and waves up to 15 feet high
lashed the coast from <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, and three people apparently
drowned and at least six others were missing.
   At <TIME>10:30 p.m. EDT</TIME>, the center of <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> was near latitude 41.0
north, longitude 60.0 west, or about 195 miles south southwest of
<LOCATION>Sable Island</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nova Scotia</LOCATION>. It was drifting north-northeast at about
12 mph and was expected to continue that course through the day.
   Also at <TIME>10:30 p.m.</TIME>, Hugo's center was near latitude 12.5 north
and longitude 31.5 west, or about 485 miles west southwest of the
southernmost <LOCATION>Cape Verde</LOCATION> islands, where many strong, peak-season
storms like <PERSON>Gabrielle</PERSON> are born. It was moving west at about 20 mph.
   Gabrielle was the seventh named storm of the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> hurricane
season and the fourth hurricane.
</TEXT>
