<HEAD>Storm Arthur Strengthens in Caribbean</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to UPDATE with storm's position at 10 p.m.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm <PERSON>Arthur</PERSON>, with heavy rains and wind up
to 70 mph, strengthened <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and forecasters warned that it
could turn into a hurricane threatening parts of <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION> and
the <LOCATION>Dominican Republic</LOCATION>.
   The Dominican Republic issued a tropical storm watch for the
south coast of the island after <PERSON>Arthur</PERSON> pushed across the <LOCATION>Windward
Islands</LOCATION> and into the <LOCATION>Caribbean Sea</LOCATION>. A similar watch was in effect
for the south coast of <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>.
   Forecasters said a hurricane watch could be issued for parts of
those areas late <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   Arthur was expected to ``remain very near to hurricane
intensity'' through early <DATE>Thursday</DATE> without reaching sustained winds
of 74 mph that would classify it as a hurricane, said <PERSON>Mark Zimmer</PERSON>,
hurricane specialist at the <ORGANIZATION>National Hurricane Center</ORGANIZATION> in suburban
<LOCATION>Coral Gables</LOCATION>.
   ``We think that there is more than a <PERCENT>50-50 percent</PERCENT> chance that
it won't become a hurricane,'' he said. ``But there is certainly
the chance that in the <DATE>next 12</DATE> to 18 hours it could go ahead and
reach hurricane intensity.''
   At <TIME>10 p.m. EDT</TIME>, <PERSON>Arthur</PERSON> was centered near latitude 14.2 north and
longitude 65.5 west, or about 420 miles southeast of <ORGANIZATION>Santo Domingo</ORGANIZATION>,
<LOCATION>Dominican Republic</LOCATION>. It was moving northwest at about 15 mph and was
expected to continue that motion through the next day or two, said
<PERSON>Bob Sheets</PERSON>, director of the hurricane center.
   Arthur, the <DATE>1990</DATE> Atlantic hurricane season's first named storm,
grew from a tropical depression, the second of the <DATE>1990</DATE> season,
that formed <DATE>Sunday</DATE> in the open <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>. The hurricane season runs
from <DATE>June 1</DATE> to <DATE>Nov. 30</DATE>.
</TEXT>
